accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith cross-cultural perspectives from contributors in nine countries, this book showcases much-needed research on current issues around migration and social work in Europe. Focusing on the reception, experiences and integration of refugees and asylum seekers, the chapters also consider the impact of recent EU policies on borders and integration. With racism on the rise in some European societies, the book foregrounds international social work values as a common framework to face discriminatory practice at macro and micro levels. Featuring recommendations for inclusive practice that ‘opens doors’, this book features the voices of migrants and the practitioners aiding their inclusion in new societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRefugeesxServices forzEurope. 0aSocial work with refugeeszEurope. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aAdeyinka, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehrendt, Malte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBombach, Clara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCabiati, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCabiati, Elena, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDaly, Maura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDebruyne, Pascal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDedotsi, Sofia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDedotsi, Sofia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDerluyn, Ilse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEkström, Elin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat